 1063–1138":"about 1063–1138","1063–1138":"1063–1138","1059–1130":"1059–1130","1076–1140":"1076–1140","1115–Female":"1115–Deceased","1025–Male":"1025–Deceased","1025–1085":"1025–1085","about 1085":"about 1085","environ 1063":"about 1063","1076":"1076","environ 1084":"about 1084","1130":"1130","1085":"1085","1140":"1140","1063":"1063","1138":"1138","1115":"1115","1059":"1059","1025":"1025","about 1115":"about 1115","Worcestershire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni":"Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","Skelton, Yorkshire, England":"Skelton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Guisborough, Everwyck, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni":"Guisborough, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Normandy, France":"Normandy, France","Dudley, Metropolitan Borough of Dudley, West Midlands, England":"Dudley, West Midlands, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Peynel","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Norfolk): variant of   Pennell   (see   Parnell  ). This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland."],"variants":[{"name":"Pennell","meanings":["English (especially southeastern):","metronym from the Middle English female personal name <i>Pennel</i> (an assimilated form of   Parnell  ).","habitational name from Penn Hall in Pensax (Worcestershire), or from either of two places called Penhill in Devon and Yorkshire, or possibly from Pendle in Lancashire. All of the placenames probably derive from British <i>penn</i> ‘head’ + Old English <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’."]}]},{"name":"Fulk","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Germanic origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. The name was originally a short form of various compound names containing the word <i>volk</i> ‘people, tribe’ (compare modern English <i>folk</i>). It has gradually died out of general use, but is still used in certain families, in particular the Grevilles. Fulke Greville, 1st Baron Brooke, was a leading figure at the court of Elizabeth I.  See also  Greville ."],"variants":[{"name":"Fulke","meanings":["Of Germanic origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. The name was originally a short form of various compound names containing the word <i>volk</i> ‘people, tribe’ (compare modern English <i>folk</i>). It has gradually died out of general use, but is still used in certain families, in particular the Grevilles. Fulke Greville, 1st Baron Brooke, was a leading figure at the court of Elizabeth I.  See also  Greville ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Fulk De Peynel was born about 1063, in Guisborough, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Guillaume De Peynel, was 40 and his mother, Lesceline de Fontenay, was 40. He married Dame Beatrix de Picquigny about 1084, in Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. He died in 1138, in Dudley, West Midlands, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 76, and was buried in Dudley, West Midlands, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"environ 1063–1138":"umbes 1063–1138","1063–1138":"1063–1138","1059–1130":"1059–1130","1076–1140":"1076–1140","1115–Female":"1115–Surnud","1025–Male":"1025–Surnud","1025–1085":"1025–1085","about 1085":"umbes 1085","environ 106